7.1 Exercises Distributions: ggplot2

Start by loading the dplyr and ggplot2 library as well as the murders and heights data.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(dslabs)
data(heights)
data(murders)
library(dplyr)

7.1.1 Qn

1. With ggplot2 plots can be saved as objects. For example we can associate a dataset with a plot object like this

p <- ggplot(data = murders)

Because data is the first argument we dont need to spell it out

p <- ggplot(murders)

and we can also use the pipe:

p <- murders %>% ggplot()

What is class of the object p?

This topic was already discussed in the book in chapter 7.2.

p <- ggplot(data=murders)
class(p)
## [1] "gg"     "ggplot"

7.1.2 Qn

2. Remember that to print an object you can use the command print or simply type the object. Print the object p defined in exercise one and describe what you see.

  1. Nothing happens.
  2. A blank slate plot.
  3. A scatterplot.
  4. A histogram.

Answer b.
Again, this was also already shown in chapter 7.2.

p <- ggplot(data=murders)
print(p)

7.1.3 Qn

3. Using the pipe %>%, create an object p but this time associated with the heights dataset instead of the murders dataset.

p <- heights %>% ggplot()
class(p)
## [1] "gg"     "ggplot"

7.1.4 Qn

4. What is the class of the object p you have just created?

Unsure which new result is supposed to be seen here, comparing to question 1 and 2. For the solution of this question see answer of question 3.
In general, the class of ggplot does not depend on the content of the data frame provided.

class(murders)
## [1] "data.frame"
class(heights)
## [1] "data.frame"
p <- murders %>% ggplot()
class(p)
## [1] "gg"     "ggplot"
p <- heights %>% ggplot()
class(p)
## [1] "gg"     "ggplot"

7.1.5 Qn

5. Now we are going to add a layer and the corresponding aesthetic mappings. For the murders data we plotted total murders versus population sizes. Explore the murders data frame to remind yourself what are the names for these two variables and select the correct answer. Hint: Look at ?murders.

  1. state and abb.
  2. total_murders and population_size.
  3. total and population.
  4. murders and size.

Answer c.
See book chapter 7.4.

qplot(murders$population/10^6, murders$total)

7.1.6 Qn

6. To create the scatterplot we add a layer with geom_point. The aesthetic mappings require us to define the x-axis and y-axis variables, respectively. So the code looks like this:

murders %>% ggplot(aes(x = , y = )) +
 geom_point()

except we have to define the two variables x and y. Fill this out with the correct variable names.

murders %>% ggplot(aes(x=population/10^6, y=total)) + geom_point()

7.1.7 Qn

7. Note that if we dont use argument names, we can obtain the same plot by making sure we enter the variable names in the right order like this:

murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total)) +
 geom_point()

Remake the plot but now with total in the x-axis and population in the y-axis.

murders %>% ggplot(aes(y=population/10^6, x=total)) + geom_point()

7.1.8 Qn

8. If instead of points we want to add text, we can use the geom_text() or geom_label() geometries. The following code

murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total)) + geom_label()

will give us the error message: Error: geom_label requires the following missing aesthetics: label

Why is this?

  1. We need to map a character to each point through the label argument in aes.
  2. We need to let geom_label know what character to use in the plot.
  3. The geom_label geometry does not require x-axis and y-axis values.
  4. geom_label is not a ggplot2 command.

Answer a.
As already pointed out in chapter 7.5, the label is an argument of aes. In the help section of geom_label it is noted, that the required arguments are x,y and label, which is why it has to be included as an argument within the aes function.

7.1.9 Qn

9. Rewrite the code above to use abbreviation as the label through aes

murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total,label = abb)) + geom_label()

7.1.10 Qn

10. Change the color of the labels to blue. How will we do this?

  1. Adding a column called blue to murders.
  2. Because each label needs a different color we map the colors through aes.
  3. Use the color argument in ggplot.
  4. Because we want all colors to be blue, we do not need to map colors, just use the color argument in geom_label.

Answer d.
Applying answer a. will result in a change of data and has no effect on the plot itself. Then by applying the solution of answer b. will result in a different color for each label. Finally, the solution in answer c.has no effect, because there is no such argument.
In general, as pointed out in chapter 7.9, the arguments in the aesthetics function aes are required, if they apply directly to the content of data: is determined by a feature of each observation If the property is independent of the data or is applied to the data as a whole, the properties are outside of aes.

7.1.11 Qn

11. Rewrite the code above to make the labels blue.

murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total,label = abb)) + geom_label(color="blue")

7.1.12 Qn

12. Now suppose we want to use color to represent the different regions. In this case which of the following is most appropriate:

  1. Adding a column called color to murders with the color we want to use.
  2. Because each label needs a different color we map the colors through the color argument of aes .
  3. Use the color argument in ggplot.
  4. Because we want all colors to be blue, we do not need to map colors, just use the color argument in geom_label.

Answer b.
This time the request is to use a different color for each label of a region, instead of a single color for all labels.

7.1.13 Qn

13. Rewrite the code above to make the labels color be determined by the states region.

murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total,label = abb,color=region)) + geom_label()

7.1.14 Qn

14. Now we are going to change the x-axis to a log scale to account for the fact the distribution of population is skewed. Lets start by defining an object p holding the plot we have made up to now

p <- murders %>% 
 ggplot(aes(population, total, label = abb, color = region)) +
 geom_label()

To change the y-axis to a log scale we learned about the scale_x_log10() function. Add this layer to the object p to change the scale and render the plot.

p <- murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total,label = abb,color=region)) + geom_label()
p + scale_x_log10()

7.1.15 Qn

15. Repeat the previous exercise but now change both axes to be in the log scale.

p <- murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total,label = abb,color=region)) + geom_label()
p + scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10()

7.1.16 Qn

16. Now edit the code above to add the title Gun murder data to the plot. Hint: use the ggtitle function.

p <- murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total,label = abb,color=region)) + geom_label()
p + scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10() + ggtitle("Gun murder data")
